Subject:    ISO standard for host names
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000007&r=1&w=2">mark () cbpavo ! cbosgd ! ATT ! COM (Mark Horton)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198609">1986-09-04 10:51:16</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026778&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026778&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I have heard the following rumor:

An ISO OSI standard recently went around for balloting.  The USA, among
other countries, voted "no" because, among other reasons, it did not
contain a plain-text (character string) representation for host names.
As a result, there is some expectation that such a standard will be
proposed as an ISO standard soon.

Much of ISO and CCITT seems to come from a left-to-right (big endian)
heritage, possibly because of the telco background of CCITT.  The ARPA
community, including much of the academic and R&amp;D community worldwide,
is using the ARPA style right-to-left (little endian) host names.
I suspect that a confrontation is on the horizon.

I understand that the US representation on this effort goes through ANSI.
Is anyone on this list, or in the ARPA community, working with ANSI on
this?  If not, you can just about be sure that ANSI will come up with
a big endian proposal.

	Mark

